### Configure Turbopack to Resolve Legacy Sass Tilde Imports

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/upgrading/version-16.mdx

Provides a `turbopack.resolveAlias` configuration in `next.config.ts` to handle legacy Sass tilde (`~`) prefixes, enabling compatibility when direct import refactoring is not feasible. This alias maps tilde-prefixed paths to direct module paths within Turbopack.

```typescript
import type { NextConfig } from 'next'

const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
  turbopack: {
    resolveAlias: {
      '~*': '*',
    },
  },
}

export default nextConfig
```

--------------------------------

### Define Multiple Loader Rules with Disjoint Conditions

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopack.mdx

Configure an array of loader rules for the same file pattern with different conditions. This example shows conditional SVG handling for browser and non-browser environments, allowing different loaders to execute based on the runtime target.

```javascript
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    rules: {
      '*.svg': [
        {
          condition: 'browser',
          loaders: ['@svgr/webpack'],
          as: '*.js',
        },
        {
          condition: { not: 'browser' },
          loaders: [require.resolve('./custom-svg-loader.js')],
          as: '*.js',
        },
      ],
    },
  },
}
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Advanced Webpack Loader Conditions in Turbopack

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopack.mdx

Set up complex loader conditions using boolean operators (all, any, not) and customizable operators (path, content) to restrict where loaders run. This example configures SVG handling with RegExp path matching and content inspection. Conditions support built-in matchers like 'foreign', 'browser', 'development', 'production', 'node', and 'edge-light'.

```javascript
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    rules: {
      '*': {
        condition: {
          all: [
            { not: 'foreign' },
            { path: /^img\/[0-9]{3}\// },
            {
              any: [
                { path: '*.svg' },
                { content: /\<svg\W/ },
              ],
            },
          ],
        },
        loaders: ['@svgr/webpack'],
        as: '*.js',
      },
    },
  },
}
```

--------------------------------

### Configure SVGR Webpack Loader with Options in Next.js

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopack.mdx

This snippet demonstrates how to pass configuration options to a webpack loader within Turbopack rules in `next.config.js`. It extends the previous example by providing the `@svgr/webpack` loader with an `icon: true` option, allowing more granular control over the loader's behavior.

```js
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    rules: {
      '*.svg': {
        loaders: [
          {
            loader: '@svgr/webpack',
            options: {
              icon: true,
            },
          },
        ],
        as: '*.js',
      },
    },
  },
}
```

--------------------------------

### Opt-in to Webpack bundler instead of Turbopack

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/local-development.mdx

Run Next.js development server with webpack bundler instead of the default Turbopack. Use this when you need to revert to webpack for compatibility or specific requirements.

```bash
npm run dev --webpack
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Module Resolution Aliases in Turbopack

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopack.mdx

Map imported module patterns to new destinations using resolveAlias in next.config.js. Supports simple string aliases and conditional aliasing for browser environments. In this example, 'underscore' imports are redirected to 'lodash', and 'mocha' imports use conditional aliasing based on the browser condition.

```javascript
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    resolveAlias: {
      underscore: 'lodash',
      mocha: { browser: 'mocha/browser-entry.js' },
    },
  },
}
```

--------------------------------

### Configure MDX Plugins for Turbopack in Next.js (`next.config.mjs`)

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/mdx.mdx

Demonstrates how to configure remark and rehype plugins using string names in `next.config.mjs` when using Next.js with Turbopack. Plugins can be specified without options, or with options passed as an array containing the plugin name and an options object. This approach is necessary because JavaScript functions cannot be serialized and passed to Rust-based Turbopack.

```js
import createMDX from '@next/mdx'

/** @type {import('next').NextConfig} */
const nextConfig = {
  pageExtensions: ['js', 'jsx', 'md', 'mdx', 'ts', 'tsx'],
}

const withMDX = createMDX({
  options: {
    remarkPlugins: [
      // Without options
      'remark-gfm',
      // With options
      ['remark-toc', { heading: 'The Table' }],
    ],
    rehypePlugins: [
      // Without options
      'rehype-slug',
      // With options
      ['rehype-katex', { strict: true, throwOnError: true }],
    ],
  },
})

export default withMDX(nextConfig)
```

