### Problem: Internal Errors Caught by try/catch

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/04-functions/unstable_rethrow.mdx

Demonstrates the issue where Next.js internal errors are caught by try/catch blocks, preventing proper framework behavior. When notFound() is called inside a try block, it throws an internal error that gets caught, stopping the not-found.js component from rendering.

```APIDOC
## Problem: Caught Internal Errors

### Issue Description
When using try/catch blocks around code that calls Next.js framework functions, the internal errors thrown by these functions get caught by the catch handler, preventing Next.js from executing its expected behavior.

### Example Problem Code
```tsx
import { notFound } from 'next/navigation'

export default async function Page() {
  try {
    const post = await fetch('https://.../posts/1').then((res) => {
      if (res.status === 404) notFound()
      if (!res.ok) throw new Error(res.statusText)
      return res.json()
    })
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err)
    // The internal error from notFound() is caught here
    // not-found.js component will NOT render
  }
}
```

### What Happens
1. fetch() returns a 404 response
2. notFound() is called, which throws an internal Next.js error
3. The catch block catches this internal error
4. The not-found.js component fails to render
5. Unexpected behavior occurs instead of proper 404 handling
```

